# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ausonius
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Aemilia was born in the Roman Empire, the area of present Moselle, France.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] She was the daughter of Caecilius Agricius Arborius and Aemilia Corinthia Maura, both poor nobles from Gaul.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Aemilia and her siblings all took the family name of their mother, which historian Hagith Sivan noted was uncommon for the time.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] It is unknown if Aemilia Hilaria was a Christian; Ausonius's phrasing seems to imply that she was, but may simply be poetic writing.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Aemilia Hilaria continued to live in the area as an adult and became a physician there.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Aemilia was the maternal aunt of Ausonius, a Gallo-Roman senator who became tutor to the Emperor Gratian.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Ausonius wrote a series of biographical poems about his family members, including Ameilia, called *Parentalia*.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Everything we know today about Aemilia Hilaria and her family comes from *Parentalia*.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Ausonius's poem about his aunt described her as a "dedicated virgin", who rejected marriage in order to further her career.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] He referenced that she loved him as if she were his mother so that he performed her last rites as a son would.
[src:ausonius/aemilia-hilaria] Aemilia is a featured figure on Judy Chicago's installation piece *The Dinner Party*, being represented as one of the 999 names on the *Heritage Floor.* She is related to the Hypatia place setting.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The **Alemanni** or **Alamanni** were a confederation of Germanic tribes on the Upper Rhine River during the 1st millennium.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In 496 AD, the Alemanni were conquered by the Frankish leader Clovis and incorporated into his dominions.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Mentioned as still pagan allies of the Christian Franks, the Alemanni were gradually Christianized during the 7th century.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The *Lex Alamannorum* is a record of their customary law during this period.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Until the 8th century, Frankish suzerainty over Alemannia was mostly nominal.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] However, after an uprising by Theudebald, the Duke of Alamannia, Carloman executed the Alamannic nobility and installed Frankish dukes.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] As the Carolingian Empire weakened in later years, the Alemannic counts became almost independent, and a struggle for supremacy took place between them and the Bishopric of Constance.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The chief family in Alamannia was that of the counts of *Raetia Curiensis*, who were sometimes called margraves, and one of whom, Burchard II, established the Duchy of Swabia, which was recognized by Henry the Fowler in 919 AD and became a stem duchy of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The area settled by the Alemanni corresponds roughly to the area where Alemannic German dialects remain spoken, including German Swabia and Baden, French Alsace, German-speaking Switzerland, Liechtenstein and Austrian Vorarlberg.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The French-language name of Germany, *Allemagne*, is derived from their name, from Old French *aleman(t)*, and from French was loaned into a number of other languages, including Middle English, which commonly used the term *Almains* for Germans.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Likewise, the Arabic name for Germany is ألمانيا (*Almanya*), the Turkish is *Almanya*, the Catalan is *Alemanya*, the Spanish is *Alemania*, the Portuguese is *Alemanha*, the Welsh is *Yr Almaen* and the Persian is آلمان (*Alman*).
[src:ausonius/alemanni] According to Gaius Asinius Quadratus (quoted in the mid-sixth century by Byzantine historian Agathias), the name *Alamanni* (Ἀλαμανοι) means "all men".
[src:ausonius/alemanni] It indicates that they were a conglomeration drawn from various Germanic tribes.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Romans and the Greeks called them as such (Alamanni, all men, in the sense of a group composed of men of all groups in the region).
[src:ausonius/alemanni] This derivation was accepted by Edward Gibbon, in his *Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* and by the anonymous contributor of notes assembled from the papers of Nicolas Fréret, published in 1753.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] This etymology has remained the standard derivation of the name.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] An alternative suggestion proposes derivation from **alah* "sanctuary".
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Walafrid Strabo in the ninth century remarked, in discussing the people of Switzerland and the surrounding regions, that only foreigners called them the Alemanni, but that they gave themselves the name of *Suebi*.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Suebi are given the alternative name of *Ziuwari* (as *Cyuuari*) in an Old High German gloss, interpreted by Jacob Grimm as *Martem colentes* ("worshippers of Mars").
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Annio da Viterbo a scholar and historian of the 15th century claimed the Alemanni had their name from the Hebrew language, as in Hebrew the river Rhine was translated into *Mannum* and the people who live at its shores were called *Alemannus*.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] This was refuted by Beatus Rhenanus, a humanist of the 16th century.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Rhenanus argued the term Alemanni was meant for the whole Germanic people only in late antiquity and before it was only meant to designate the population of an island in the North Sea.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Early Roman writers did not mention the Alemanni, and it is likely that they had not yet come to exist.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In his *Germania* Tacitus (AD 90) does not mention the Alemanni.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] He uses the term Agri Decumates to describe the region between the Rhine, Main and Danube rivers.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] He says that it had once been the home of the Helvetians, who had moved westwards into Gaul in the time of Julius Caesar.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The people living there in Caesar's time are not Germanic.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Instead, "Reckless adventurers from Gaul, emboldened by want, occupied this land of questionable ownership.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Alemanni were first mentioned by Cassius Dio describing the campaign of Caracalla in 213.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] At that time, they apparently dwelt in the basin of the Main, to the south of the Chatti.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Cassius Dio portrays the Alemanni as victims of this treacherous emperor.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] They had asked for his help, according to Dio, but instead he colonized their country, changed their place names, and executed their warriors under a pretext of coming to their aid.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] When he became ill, the Alemanni claimed to have put a hex on him.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Caracalla, it was claimed, tried to counter this influence by invoking his ancestral spirits.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In retribution, Caracalla then led the Legio II *Traiana Fortis* against the Alemanni, who lost and were pacified for a time.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Through much of his short reign, Caracalla was known for unpredictable and arbitrary operations launched by surprise after a pretext of peace negotiations.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] If he had any reasons of state for such actions, they remained unknown to his contemporaries.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Whether or not the Alemanni had been previously neutral, they were certainly further influenced by Caracalla to become thereafter notoriously implacable enemies of Rome.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Most of the Alemanni were probably at the time, in fact, resident in or close to the borders of Germania Superior.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Although Dio is the earliest writer to mention them, Ammianus Marcellinus used the name to refer to Germans on the Limes Germanicus in the time of Trajan's governorship of the province shortly after it was formed, around 98–99 AD.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] At that time, the entire frontier was being fortified for the first time.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Trees from the earliest fortifications found in Germania Inferior are dated by dendrochronology to 99–100 AD.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Ammianus relates (xvii.1.11) that much later the Emperor Julian undertook a punitive expedition against the Alemanni, who by then were in Alsace, and crossed the Main (Latin *Menus*), entering the forest, where the trails were blocked by felled trees.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] As winter was upon them, they reoccupied a "fortification which was founded on the soil of the Alemanni that Trajan wished to be called with his own name".
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In this context, the use of Alemanni is possibly an anachronism, but it reveals that Ammianus believed they were the same people, which is consistent with the location of the Alemanni of Caracalla's campaigns.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Alemanni were continually engaged in conflicts with the Roman Empire in the third and fourth centuries.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] They launched a major invasion of Gaul and northern Italy in 268 when the Romans were forced to denude much of their German frontier of troops in response to a massive invasion of the Goths from the east.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] And coming to Clermont he set on fire, overthrew and destroyed that shrine which they call *Vasso Galatae* in the Gallic tongue," martyring many Christians (*Historia Francorum* Book I.32–34).
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Thus sixth-century Gallo-Romans of Gregory's class, surrounded by the ruins of Roman temples and public buildings, attributed the destruction they saw to the plundering raids of the Alemanni.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In the early summer of 268, the Emperor Gallienus halted their advance into Italy but then had to deal with the Goths.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] When the Gothic campaign ended in Roman victory at the Battle of Naissus in September, Gallienus's successor Claudius Gothicus turned north to deal with the Alemanni, who were swarming over all Italy north of the Po River.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] After efforts to secure a peaceful withdrawal failed, Claudius forced the Alemanni to battle at the Battle of Lake Benacus in November.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Alemanni were routed, forced back into Germany, and did not threaten Roman territory for many years afterwards.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Their most famous battle against Rome took place in Argentoratum (Strasbourg), in 357, where they were defeated by Julian, later Emperor of Rome, and their king Chnodomarius was taken prisoner to Rome.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] On January 2, 366, the Alemanni yet again crossed the frozen Rhine in large numbers, to invade the Gallic provinces, this time being defeated by Valentinian (see Battle of Solicinium).
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In the great mixed invasion of 406, the Alemanni appear to have crossed the Rhine river a final time, conquering and then settling what is today Alsace and a large part of the Swiss Plateau.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The crossing is described in Wallace Breem's historical novel *Eagle in the Snow*.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Chronicle of Fredegar gives the account.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] At *Alba Augusta* (Alba-la-Romaine) the devastation was so complete, that the Christian bishop retired to Viviers, but in Gregory's account at Mende in Lozère, also deep in the heart of Gaul, bishop Privatus was forced to sacrifice to idols in the very cave where he was later venerated.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] It is thought this detail may be a generic literary ploy to epitomize the horrors of barbarian violence.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The kingdom of Alamannia between Strasbourg and Augsburg lasted until 496, when the Alemanni were conquered by Clovis I at the Battle of Tolbiac.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The war of Clovis with the Alemanni forms the setting for the conversion of Clovis, briefly treated by Gregory of Tours.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] (Book II.31) After their defeat in 496, the Alemanni bucked the Frankish yoke and put themselves under the protection of Theodoric the Great of the Ostrogoths but after his death they were again subjugated by the Franks under Theudebert I in 536.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Subsequently, the Alemanni formed part of the Frankish dominions and were governed by a Frankish duke.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In 746, Carloman ended an uprising by summarily executing all Alemannic nobility at the blood court at Cannstatt, and for the following century, Alemannia was ruled by Frankish dukes.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Following the treaty of Verdun of 843, Alemannia became a province of the eastern kingdom of Louis the German, the precursor of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The German spoken today over the range of the former Alemanni is termed Alemannic German, and is recognised among the subgroups of the High German languages.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Alemannic runic inscriptions such as those on the Pforzen buckle are among the earliest testimonies of Old High German.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The High German consonant shift is thought to have originated around the fifth century either in Alemannia or among the Lombards; before that, the dialect spoken by Alemannic tribes was little different from that of other West Germanic peoples.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Alemanni established a series of territorially defined *pagi* (cantons) on the east bank of the Rhine.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The exact number and extent of these *pagi* is unclear and probably changed over time.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Christianization of the Alemanni took place during Merovingian times (sixth to eighth centuries).
[src:ausonius/alemanni] We know that in the sixth century, the Alemanni were predominantly pagan, and in the eighth century, they were predominantly Christian.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The intervening seventh century was a period of genuine syncretism during which Christian symbolism and doctrine gradually grew in influence.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Some scholars have speculated that members of the Alemannic elite such as king Gibuld due to Visigothic influence may have been converted to Arianism even in the later fifth century.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] He also spoke of the particular ruthlessness of the Alemanni in destroying Christian sanctuaries and plundering churches while the genuine Franks were respectful towards those sanctuaries.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Agathias expresses his hope that the Alemanni would assume better manners through prolonged contact with the Franks, which is by all appearances, in a manner of speaking, what eventually happened.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Apostles of the Alemanni were Columbanus and his disciple Saint Gall.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Jonas of Bobbio records that Columbanus was active in Bregenz, where he disrupted a beer sacrifice to Wodan.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Despite these activities, for some time, the Alemanni seem to have continued their pagan cult activities, with only superficial or syncretistic Christian elements.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In particular, there was no change in burial practice, and tumulus warrior graves continued to be erected throughout Merovingian times.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Syncretism of traditional Germanic animal style with Christian symbolism is also present in artwork, but Christian symbolism became more and more prevalent during the seventh century.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Unlike the later Christianization of the Saxons and of the Slavs, the Alemanni seem to have adopted Christianity gradually, and voluntarily, spread in emulation of the Merovingian elite.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] From c. the 520s to the 620s, there was a surge of Alemannic Elder Futhark inscriptions.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] About 70 specimens have survived, roughly half of them on fibulae, others on belt buckles (see Pforzen buckle, Bülach fibula) and other jewellery and weapon parts.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The use of runes subsides with the advance of Christianity.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The Nordendorf fibula (early seventh century) clearly records pagan theonyms, *logaþorewodanwigiþonar* read as "Wodan and Donar are magicians/sorcerers", but this may be interpreted as either a pagan invocation of the powers of these deities, or a Christian protective charm against them.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] A runic inscription on a fibula found at Bad Ems reflects Christian pious sentiment (and is also explicitly marked with a Christian cross), reading *god fura dih deofile ᛭* ("God for/before you, Theophilus!", or alternatively "God before you, Devil!").
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Dated to between AD 660 and 690, it marks the end of the native Alemannic tradition of runic literacy.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Bad Ems is in Rhineland-Palatinate, on the northwestern boundary of Alemannic settlement, where Frankish influence would have been strongest.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The establishment of the bishopric of Konstanz cannot be dated exactly and was possibly undertaken by Columbanus himself (before 612).
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In any case, it existed by 635, when Gunzo appointed John of Grab bishop.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Constance was a missionary bishopric in newly converted lands, and did not look back on late Roman church history unlike the Raetian bishopric of Chur (established 451) and Basel (an episcopal seat from 740, and which continued the line of Bishops of Augusta Raurica, see Bishop of Basel).
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The establishment of the church as an institution recognized by worldly rulers is also visible in legal history.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] In the early seventh century *Pactus Alamannorum* hardly ever mentions the special privileges of the church, while Lantfrid's *Lex Alamannorum* of 720 has an entire chapter reserved for ecclesial matters alone.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] A genetic study published in *Science Advances* in September 2018 examined the remains of eight individuals buried at a seventh-century Alemannic graveyard in Niederstotzingen, Germany.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] This is the richest and most complete Alemannic graveyard ever found.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The highest-ranking individual at the graveyard was a male with Frankish grave goods.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Four males were found to be closely related to him.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] They were all carriers of types of the paternal haplogroup R1b1a2a1a1c2b2b.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] A sixth male was a carrier of the paternal haplogroup R1b1a2a1a1c2b2b1a1 and the maternal haplogroup U5a1a1.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Along with the five closely related individuals, he displayed close genetic links to northern and eastern Europe, particularly Lithuania and Iceland.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Two individuals buried at the cemetery were found to be genetically different from both the others and each other, displaying genetic links to Southern Europe, particularly northern Italy and Spain.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] Along with the sixth male, they might have been adoptees or slaves.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] The data indicate a significant increase in Scandinavian-related ancestry—a proxy for Germanic-speaking groups—in the first half of the first millennium AD, with "median northern European ancestry" rising significantly, reaching high levels in the early medieval period.
[src:ausonius/alemanni] This population turnover was associated with the introduction of new paternal haplogroups, such as I1-M253, which is commonly found in "Continental North European-like ancestry".
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] There are also several historical forms.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:ausonius/ancient-greek-language] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:ausonius/arles] A large part of the Camargue, the largest wetlands in France, is located within the territory of the commune, which is the largest in Metropolitan France in terms of geographic territory.
[src:ausonius/arles] In non-metropolitan France, Maripasoula in French Guiana is the largest French commune in general.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city has a long history, and was of considerable importance in the Roman province of Gallia Narbonensis.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Roman and Romanesque Monuments of Arles were listed as UNESCO World Heritage Sites in 1981 for their testimony to the history of the region.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city is famous for being the archdiocese of Caesarius of Arles and Hilary of Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] Additionally, many artists have lived and worked in this area, including Pablo Picasso, Paul Gauguin and Jacques Réattu.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Dutch post-Impressionist painter Vincent van Gogh lived in Arles from 1888 to 1889, and produced over 300 paintings and drawings during his time there.
[src:ausonius/arles] These are held in internationally known museums and private collections around the world.
[src:ausonius/arles] An international photography festival has been held annually in the city since 1970.
[src:ausonius/arles] The settlement is attested as *Arelate* in the mid-1st century BC (Caesar), *Areláte* (Ἀρελάτη) in the early 1st c.
[src:ausonius/arles] AD (Strabo), *Arlate civitas* in 954, and *Arle* in the 13th century.
[src:ausonius/arles] The toponym *Arelate* is a Latinized form of the Gaulish **Arelati*, meaning 'by the marsh', or 'in front of the marsh'.
[src:ausonius/arles] The river Rhône forks into two branches just upstream of Arles, forming the Camargue delta.
[src:ausonius/arles] Because the Camargue is for a large part administratively part of Arles, the commune as a whole is the largest in Metropolitan France.
[src:ausonius/arles] Over seven times greater in area than Paris, Arles occupies 758.93 km2 (293.02 sq mi) and has a population of 51,156.
[src:ausonius/arles] In addition to the city proper in the north of the territory, the commune of Arles includes a number of outlying towns and hamlets, including Albaron, Gageron, Mas-Thibert, Moulès, Pont-de-Crau, Raphèle-lès-Arles, Saliers, Salin-de-Giraud and Le Sambuc.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Ligurians were in this area from about 800 BC.
[src:ausonius/arles] Later Celtic influences have also been discovered.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city became an important Greek (from Messalia) and Phoenician trading port, before it was taken over by the Romans.
[src:ausonius/arles] In the 6th century BCE, Greek merchants sailed up the Rhône river, 38 km north of the Mediterranean coast discovering a hill surrounded by wetland marshes and inhabited by a small tribe of Ligures.
[src:ausonius/arles] Archaelogical digs have shown they used greek furniture, indicating Arles was established as a Greek trading base.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Greeks had already founded Marseille (Messalia) and the Greek merchants saw potential in this new site.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles was on a geographical important location, the first place to cross the Rhône from the sea.
[src:ausonius/arles] It also was at the intersection of major trade routes, and the main route from Italy to Spain.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Romans took the town in 123 BC and expanded it into an important city.
[src:ausonius/arles] They built a canal link to the Mediterranean Sea in 104 BC.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles had to compete with Massalia (Marseille) further along the coast.
[src:ausonius/arles] The recently discovered republican House of the Harpist is an exceptional example of ancient architecture and interior decoration.
[src:ausonius/arles] Dating from 70-50 BC, it has yielded elaborate frescoes.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles' leaders sided with Julius Caesar against Pompey, providing military support.
[src:ausonius/arles] Massalia backed Pompey; when Caesar emerged victorious, Massalia was stripped of its possessions, which were transferred to Arelate as a reward.
[src:ausonius/arles] The town was formally established as a colony for veterans of the Roman legion Legio VI *Ferrata*, which had its base there.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arelate was a city of considerable importance in the province of Gallia Narbonensis.
[src:ausonius/arles] It covered an area of some 40 hectares (99 acres) and possessed a number of monuments, including an amphitheatre, triumphal arch, Roman circus, theatre, and a full circuit of walls.
[src:ausonius/arles] Ancient Arles was closer to the sea than it is now and served as a major port.
[src:ausonius/arles] The river has carried centuries of silt that has filled in the former harbor.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city had (and still has) the southernmost bridge on the Rhône.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Roman bridge was unique in that it was not fixed but consisted of a pontoon-style bridge of boats, with towers and drawbridges at each end.
[src:ausonius/arles] The boats were secured in place by anchors and were tethered to twin towers built just upstream of the bridge.
[src:ausonius/arles] This unusual design was a way of coping with the river's frequent violent floods, which would have made short work of a conventional bridge.
[src:ausonius/arles] Nothing remains of the Roman bridge, which has been replaced by a more modern bridge near the same spot.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city reached a peak of influence during the 4th and 5th centuries, when Roman Emperors frequently used it as their headquarters during military campaigns in Europe.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 395, it became the seat of the Praetorian Prefecture of the Gauls, governing the western part of the Western Empire: Gaul proper plus Hispania (Spain) and Armorica (Brittany).
[src:ausonius/arles] At that time, the city was home to an estimated 75,000–100,000 people.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city also dominated the Rhone Valley, the main connection between North Gaul, Italy and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ausonius/arles] This natural corridor between the Central Massive and the Alps was a crucial route for troop movements, communication and supply.
[src:ausonius/arles] Those who controlled Arles actually controlled strategic access to Gaul.
[src:ausonius/arles] It was often the subject of hostilities for that reason, especially in the 5th century.
[src:ausonius/arles] It became a favorite city of Emperor Constantine I, who built baths there, substantial remains of which are still standing.
[src:ausonius/arles] His son, Constantine II, was born in Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] Usurper Constantine III declared himself emperor in the West (407–411) and made Arles his capital in 408.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles became renowned as a cultural and religious centre during the late Roman Empire.
[src:ausonius/arles] It was the birthplace of Favorinus, known as the sceptical philosopher.
[src:ausonius/arles] It was also a key location for Roman Christianity and an important base for the Christianization of Gaul.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city's bishopric was held by a series of outstanding clerics, beginning with Saint Trophimus around 225 and continuing with Saint Honoratus, then Saint Hilarius in the first half of the 5th century.
[src:ausonius/arles] The political tension between the Catholic bishops of Arles and the Visigothic kings is epitomized in the career of the Frankish St.
[src:ausonius/arles] Suspected by the Arian Visigoth Alaric II of conspiring with the Burgundians to turn over the Arelate to Burgundy, he was exiled for a year to Bordeaux in Aquitaine.
[src:ausonius/arles] Political tensions were evident again in 512, when Arles held out against Theodoric the Great.
[src:ausonius/arles] Caesarius was imprisoned and sent to Ravenna to explain his actions before the Ostrogothic king.
[src:ausonius/arles] The friction between the Arian Christianity of the Visigoths and the Catholicism of the bishops sent out from Rome established deep roots for religious heterodoxy, even heresy, in Occitan culture.
[src:ausonius/arles] At Treves in 385, Priscillian achieved the distinction of becoming the first Christian executed for heresy (Manichaean in his case, see also Cathars, Camisards).
[src:ausonius/arles] Despite this tension and the city's decline in the face of barbarian invasions, Arles remained a great religious centre.
[src:ausonius/arles] It hosted church councils (see Council of Arles), the rival of Vienne, for hundreds of years.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Barbegal aqueduct and mill is a Roman watermill complex located on the territory of the commune of Fontvieille, a few kilometres from Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] The complex has been referred to as "the greatest known concentration of mechanical power in the ancient world".
[src:ausonius/arles] The remains of the mill streams and buildings which housed the overshot water wheels are still visible at the site, and it is by far the best-preserved of ancient mills.
[src:ausonius/arles] There are two aqueducts which join just north of the mill complex, and a sluice which enabled the operators to control the water supply to the complex.
[src:ausonius/arles] The mill consisted of 16 water wheels in two separate rows built into a steep hillside.
[src:ausonius/arles] There are substantial masonry remains of the water channels and foundations of the individual mills, together with a staircase rising up the hill upon which the mills are built.
[src:ausonius/arles] The mills apparently operated from the end of the 1st century until about the end of the 3rd century.
[src:ausonius/arles] The capacity of the mills has been estimated at 4.5 tons of flour per day, sufficient to supply enough bread for 12,000 of the 30,000–40,000 inhabitants of Arelate at that time.
[src:ausonius/arles] A similar mill complex existed also on the Janiculum in Rome.
[src:ausonius/arles] Examination of the mill leat still just visible on one side of the hill shows a substantial accretion of lime in the channel, tending to confirm its long working life.
[src:ausonius/arles] It is thought that the wheels were overshot water wheels with the outflow from the top driving the next one down and so on, to the base of the hill.
[src:ausonius/arles] Vertical water mills were well known to the Romans, being described by Vitruvius in his *De Architectura* of 25 BC, and mentioned by Pliny the Elder in his Natural History of 77 AD.
[src:ausonius/arles] There are also later references to floating water mills from Byzantium and to sawmills on the river Moselle by the poet Ausonius.
[src:ausonius/arles] The use of multiple stacked sequences of reverse overshot water wheels was widespread in Roman mines.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 735, after raiding the Lower Rhône, Andalusian Saracens led by Yusuf ibn 'Abd al-Rahman al-Fihri moved into the stronghold summoned by Count Maurontus, who feared Charles Martel's expansionist ambitions, though this may have been an excuse to further Muslim expansion beyond Iberia.
[src:ausonius/arles] The next year, Charles campaigned south to Septimania and Provence, attacking and capturing Arles from the Muslim Arabs after destroying Avignon.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 739, Charles definitively drove Maurontus to exile, and brought Provence to heel.
[src:ausonius/arles] Louis the Pious, in 829, placed Arles under royal protection and assigned it with special privileges.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 855, it was made the capital of a Frankish Kingdom of Burgundy, which included Burgundy and part of Provence, but was frequently terrorised by Saracen and Viking raiders.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 888, Rudolph, Count of Auxerre (now in north-western Burgundy), founded the kingdom of Transjuran Burgundy (literally, beyond the Jura mountains), which included western Switzerland as far as the river Reuss, Valais, Geneva, Chablais and Bugey.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 933, Hugh of Arles ("Hugues de Provence") gave his kingdom up to Rudolph II, who merged the two kingdoms into a new Kingdom of Burgundy-Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 1032, King Rudolph III died, and the kingdom was inherited by Emperor Conrad II the Salic.
[src:ausonius/arles] Though his successors counted themselves kings of Arles, few went to be crowned in the cathedral.
[src:ausonius/arles] Most of the kingdom's territory was progressively incorporated into France.
[src:ausonius/arles] During these troubled times, the amphitheatre was converted into a fortress, with watchtowers built at each of the four quadrants and a minuscule walled town being constructed within.
[src:ausonius/arles] The population was by now only a fraction of what it had been in Roman times, with much of old Arles lying in ruins.
[src:ausonius/arles] The town regained political and economic prominence in the 12th century, with the Holy Roman Emperor Frederick Barbarossa traveling there in 1178 for his coronation.
[src:ausonius/arles] In the 12th century, it became a free city governed by an elected *podestat* (chief magistrate; literally "power"), who appointed the consuls and other magistrates.
[src:ausonius/arles] It retained this status until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles joined the countship of Provence in 1239, but, once more, its prominence was eclipsed by Marseilles.
[src:ausonius/arles] In 1378, the Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV made the Dauphin of France (later King Charles VI of France) vicar of the moribund Kingdom of Burgundy-Arles for his lifetime.
[src:ausonius/arles] The kingdom ceased to have any political existence soon afterwards.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles remained economically important for many years as a major port on the Rhône.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Hôtel de Ville was completed in 1676.
[src:ausonius/arles] In the 19th century, the establishment of railways diminished river trade, leading to the city declining in prominence.
[src:ausonius/arles] This made it a destination for the painter Vincent van Gogh, who arrived there on 21 February 1888.
[src:ausonius/arles] He was fascinated by the Provençal landscapes, producing over 300 paintings and drawings during his time in Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] Many of his most famous paintings were completed there, including *The Night Cafe*, the *Yellow Room*, *Starry Night Over the Rhone*, and *L'Arlésienne*.
[src:ausonius/arles] However, van Gogh's mental health deteriorated and he became alarmingly eccentric, culminating in the ear-severing incident in December 1888 which resulted in two stays in the Old Hospital of Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] The concerned Arlesians circulated a petition the following February demanding that van Gogh be confined.
[src:ausonius/arles] In May 1889, he voluntarily left Arles for the Saint-Paul asylum at nearby Saint-Rémy-de-Provence.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles had an important and prominent Jewish community between the Roman era and the end of the 15th century.
[src:ausonius/arles] A local legend describes the first Jews in Arles as exiles from Judaea after Jerusalem fell to the Romans.
[src:ausonius/arles] Nevertheless, the first documented evidence of Jews in Arles is not before the fifth century, when a distinguished community already existed in the town.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles was an important Jewish crossroads, as a port city and close to Spain and the rest of Europe alike.
[src:ausonius/arles] It served a major role in the work of the Hachmei Provence group of famous Jewish scholars, translators and philosophers, who were most important to Judaism throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:ausonius/arles] In the eighth century, jurisdiction over the Jews of Arles was passed to the local Archbishop, making the Jewish taxes to the clergy somewhat of a shield for the community from mob attacks, most frequent during the Crusades.
[src:ausonius/arles] The community lived relatively peacefully until the last decade of the 15th century, when they were expelled from the city never to return.
[src:ausonius/arles] Several Jews did live in the city in the centuries after, though no community was found ever after.
[src:ausonius/arles] Nowadays, Jewish archaeological findings and texts from Arles can be found in the local museum.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles has a hot summer Mediterranean climate (Köppen: *Csa*) with a mean annual temperature of 14.6 °C (1948–1999).
[src:ausonius/arles] The summers are warm and moderately dry, with seasonal averages between 22 °C and 24 °C, and cool to mild winters with a mean temperature of about 7 °C.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city is constantly, but especially in the winter months, subject to the influence of the mistral, a cold wind which can cause sudden and severe frosts.
[src:ausonius/arles] Rainfall (636 mm per year) is fairly evenly distributed from September to May, with the summer drought being less marked than in other Mediterranean areas.
[src:ausonius/arles] The population data in the table and graph below refer to the commune of Arles proper, in its geography at the given years.
[src:ausonius/arles] The commune of Arles ceded part of its territory to the new commune of Port-Saint-Louis-du-Rhône in 1904, and to the new commune of Saint-Martin-de-Crau in 1925.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles has important Roman remnants, most of which have been listed as UNESCO World Heritage Sites since 1981 within the Arles, Roman and Romanesque Monuments group.
[src:ausonius/arles] The town also has a museum of ancient history, the Musée de l'Arles et de la Provence antiques, with one of the best collections of Roman sarcophagi to be found anywhere outside Rome itself.
[src:ausonius/arles] Other museums include the Musée Réattu and the Museon Arlaten.
[src:ausonius/arles] The courtyard of the Old Arles hospital, now named "Espace Van Gogh," is a center for Vincent van Gogh's works, several of which are masterpieces.
[src:ausonius/arles] The garden, framed on all four sides by buildings of the complex, is approached through arcades on the first floor.
[src:ausonius/arles] A circulation gallery is located on the first and second floors.
[src:ausonius/arles] The LUMA Tower is a 56-meter tall construction, the center of the LUMA Arles arts center.
[src:ausonius/arles] The larger bust was tentatively dated to 46 BC.
[src:ausonius/arles] The story was picked up by all larger media outlets.
[src:ausonius/arles] The realism of the portrait was said to place it in the tradition of late Republican portrait and genre sculptures.
[src:ausonius/arles] The archaeologists further claimed that a bust of Julius Caesar might have been thrown away or discreetly disposed of, because Caesar's portraits could have been viewed as politically dangerous possessions after the dictator's assassination.
[src:ausonius/arles] Historians and archaeologists not affiliated with the French administration, among them Paul Zanker, an archaeologist and expert on Caesar and Augustus, were quick to question whether the bust is a portrait of Caesar.
[src:ausonius/arles] Many noted the lack of resemblances to Caesar's likenesses issued on coins during the last years of the dictator's life, and to the Tusculum bust of Caesar, which depicts Julius Caesar in his lifetime, either as a so-called *zeitgesicht* or as a direct portrait.
[src:ausonius/arles] After a further stylistic assessment, Zanker dated the Arles-bust to the Augustan period.
[src:ausonius/arles] Elkins argued for the third century AD as the *terminus post quem* for the deposition of the statues, refuting the claim that the bust was thrown away due to feared repercussions from Caesar's assassination in 44 BC.
[src:ausonius/arles] The main argument by the French archaeologists that Caesar had founded the colony in 46 BC proved to be incorrect, as the colony was founded by Caesar's former quaestor Tiberius Claudius Nero on the dictator's orders in his absence.
[src:ausonius/arles] Mary Beard has accused the persons involved in the find of having willfully invented their claims for publicity reasons.
[src:ausonius/arles] The French ministry of culture has not yet responded to the criticism and negative reviews.
[src:ausonius/arles] AC Arles-Avignon was a professional French football team.
[src:ausonius/arles] They previously played in Championnat de France Amateur, the fourth division in French football, but were dissolved in 2016.
[src:ausonius/arles] They play at the Parc des Sports, which has a capacity of just over 17,000.
[src:ausonius/arles] A well known photography festival, Rencontres d'Arles, takes place in Arles every year.
[src:ausonius/arles] The major French publishing house Actes Sud is also situated in Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] In the past years, several cultural organizations have set up a presence in Arles, such as the LUMA Foundation, the *Fondation Vincent van Gogh Arles*, the Manuel Rivera-Ortiz Foundation or the Lee Ufan Foundation.
[src:ausonius/arles] On top of that, there are countless galleries scattered throughout the city.
[src:ausonius/arles] Bullfights are conducted in the amphitheatre, including Provençal-style bullfights (*courses camarguaises*) in which the bull is not killed, but rather a team of athletic men attempt to remove a tassle from the bull's horn without getting injured.
[src:ausonius/arles] Every Easter and on the first weekend of September, during the feria, Arles also holds Spanish-style *corridas* (in which the bulls are killed) with an *encierro* (bull-running in the streets) preceding each fight.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles played a major role in Marseille-Provence 2013, the year-long series of cultural events held in the region after it was designated the European Capital of Culture for 2013.
[src:ausonius/arles] The city hosted a segment of the opening ceremony with a pyrotechnical performance by Groupe F on the banks of the Rhône.
[src:ausonius/arles] It also unveiled the new wing of the Musée Départemental Arles Antique as part of Marseille-Provence 2013.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles's open-air street market is a major market in the region.
[src:ausonius/arles] It takes place on Saturday and Wednesday mornings.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Gare d'Arles railway station offers connections to Avignon, Nîmes, Marseille, Paris, Bordeaux and several regional destinations.
[src:ausonius/arles] Arles does not have its own commercial airport, but is served by a number of airports in the region, most notably the major international airport of Marseille Provence approximately an hour's drive away.
[src:ausonius/arles] The A54 autoroute toll motorway, which locally connects Salon-de-Provence with Nîmes and in a wider sense forms part of European route E80, passes by Arles.
[src:ausonius/arles] The Rhône, which for navigation purposes is classified as a Class V waterway as far upstream as Lyon, is a historically important transport route connecting the inland Rhône-Alpes region with the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ausonius/arles] The port of Arles and its adjacent rail and road connections provides a major transshipment node, which in 2013 handled approximately 450,000 tonnes of goods.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] During the Neolithic period, Anatolia was an early center for the development of farming after it originated in the adjacent Fertile Crescent.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Beginning around 9,000 years ago, there was a major migration of Anatolian neolithic farmers into Europe, with their descendants coming to dominate the continent as far west as the Iberian Peninsula and the British Isles.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The earliest recorded inhabitants of Anatolia, such as the Hattians, who were neither Indo-European nor Semitic, were gradually absorbed by the incoming Indo-European Anatolian peoples, who spoke the now-extinct Anatolian languages.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The major Anatolian languages included Hittite, Luwian, and Lydian; other local languages, albeit poorly attested, included Phrygian and Mysian.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Hurro-Urartian languages were spoken throughout Mitanni in the southeast, while Galatian, a Celtic language, was spoken throughout Galatia in the central peninsula.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Among the other peoples who established a significant presence in ancient Anatolia were the Galatians, the Hurrians, the Assyrians, the Armenians, the Hattians, and the Cimmerians, as well as some of the ancient Greek tribes, including the Ionians, the Dorians, and the Aeolians.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In the era of classical antiquity (see Classical Anatolia), the Anatolian languages were largely replaced by the Greek language, which came to dominate a large region during the Hellenistic period and the Roman period.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Byzantine period saw the height and eventual decline of Greek influence throughout the peninsula as the Byzantine–Seljuk wars enabled the incoming Seljuk Turks to establish a foothold in the region.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Thus, the process of Anatolia's Turkification began under the Seljuk Empire in the late 11th century and continued under the Ottoman Empire until the early 20th century, when the Ottoman dynasty collapsed in the aftermath of World War I.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Between 1894 and 1924, millions of non-Turkic peoples and Christians, especially Greeks (about two million) and Armenians (est.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] 1.5 million), were killed by the Ottoman Turkish authorities or expelled from the bulk of the area of modern-day Turkey.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Nonetheless, a variety of non-Turkic languages continue to be spoken by ethnic minorities in Anatolia today, including Arabic, Kurdish, Neo-Aramaic, Armenian, the North Caucasian languages, Laz, Georgian, and Greek.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Traditionally, Anatolia is considered to extend in the east to an indefinite line running from the Gulf of Alexandretta to the Black Sea, coterminous with the Anatolian Plateau.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] This traditional geographical definition is used, for example, in the latest edition of *Merriam-Webster's Geographical Dictionary*.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Under this definition, Anatolia is bounded to the east by the Armenian Highlands, and the Euphrates before that river bends to the southeast to enter Mesopotamia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] To the southeast, it is bounded by the ranges that separate it from the Orontes valley in Syria and the Mesopotamian plain.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Following the Armenian genocide, Western Armenia was renamed the Eastern Anatolia region by the newly established Turkish government.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In 1941, with the First Geography Congress which divided Turkey into seven geographical regions based on differences in climate and landscape, the eastern provinces of Turkey were placed into the Eastern Anatolia region, which largely corresponds to the historical region of Western Armenia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The highest mountain in the Eastern Anatolia region (also the highest peak in the Armenian Highlands) is Mount Ararat (5123 m).
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Euphrates, Aras, Karasu and Murat rivers connect the Armenian Highlands to the South Caucasus and the Upper Euphrates Valley.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Along with the Çoruh, these rivers are the longest in the Eastern Anatolia region.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The English-language name *Anatolia* derives from the Greek Ἀνατολή (*Anatolḗ*) meaning "the East" and designating (from a Greek point of view) eastern regions in general.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The use of Anatolian designations has varied over time, perhaps originally referring to the Aeolian, Ionian and Dorian colonies situated along the eastern coasts of the Aegean Sea, but also encompassing eastern regions in general.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Such use of Anatolian designations was employed during the reign of Roman Emperor Diocletian (r.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] 284–305), who created the Diocese of the East, known in Greek as the Eastern Diocese, but completely unrelated to the regions of Asia Minor.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Only after the loss of other eastern regions during the 7th century and the reduction of Byzantine eastern domains to Asia Minor, that region became the only remaining part of the *Byzantine East*, and thus commonly referred to (in Greek) as the Eastern part of the Empire.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] At the same time, the Anatolic Theme (Ἀνατολικὸν θέμα / "the Eastern theme") was created, as a province (*theme*) covering the western and central parts of Turkey's present-day Central Anatolia Region, centered around Iconium, but ruled from the city of Amorium.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Latinised form "Anatolia", with its *-ia* ending, is probably a Medieval Latin innovation.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The modern Turkish form *Anadolu* derives directly from the Greek name Ἀνατολή (*Anatolḗ*).
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Russian male name Anatoly, the French Anatole and plain Anatol, all stemming from saints Anatolius of Laodicea (d.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] 283) and Anatolius of Constantinople (d.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] 458; the first Patriarch of Constantinople), share the same linguistic origin.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The oldest known name for any region within Anatolia is related to its central area, known as the "Land of Hatti" – a designation that was initially used for the land of ancient Hattians, but later became the most common name for the entire territory under the rule of ancient Hittites.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The first recorded name the Greeks used for the Anatolian peninsula, though not particularly popular at the time, was Ἀσία (*Asía*), perhaps from an Akkadian expression for the "sunrise" or possibly echoing the name of the Assuwa league in western Anatolia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Romans used it as the name of their province, comprising the west of the peninsula plus the nearby Aegean Islands.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The endonym Ῥωμανία (*Rōmanía* "the land of the Romans, i.e. the Eastern Roman Empire") was understood as another name for the province by the invading Seljuq Turks, who founded a Sultanate of Rûm in 1077.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Thus (land of the) Rûm became another name for Anatolia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] By the 12th century Europeans had started referring to Anatolia as *Turchia*.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] During the era of the Ottoman Empire, many mapmakers referred to the mountainous plateau in eastern Anatolia as Armenia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Other contemporary sources called the same area Kurdistan.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Geographers have used *East Anatolian plateau*, *Armenian plateau* and the *Iranian plateau* to refer to the region; the former two largely overlap.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] While a standard definition of Anatolia refers to the entire Asian side of Turkey, according to archaeologist Lori Khatchadourian, this difference in terminology "primarily result[s] from the shifting political fortunes and cultural trajectories of the region since the nineteenth century".
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] According to Richard Hovannisian, this changing of toponyms was "necessary to obscure all evidence" of the Armenian presence as part of the policy of Armenian genocide denial embarked upon by the newly established Turkish government and what Hovannisian calls its "foreign collaborators".
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Human habitation in Anatolia dates back to the Paleolithic.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Neolithic settlements include Çatalhöyük, Çayönü, Nevali Cori, Aşıklı Höyük, Boncuklu Höyük, Hacilar, Göbekli Tepe, Norşuntepe, Köşk Höyük, and Yumuktepe. Çatalhöyük (7,000 BCE) is considered the most advanced of these.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Recent advances in archaeogenetics have confirmed that the spread of agriculture from the Middle East to Europe was strongly correlated with the migration of early farmers from Anatolia about 9,000 years ago, and was not just a cultural exchange.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolian Neolithic farmers derived most of their ancestry from local Anatolian hunter-gatherers, suggesting that agriculture was adopted in site by these hunter-gatherers and not spread by demic diffusion into the region.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolian-derived Neolithic Farmers would subsequently spread across Europe, as far west as the Iberian Peninsula and the British Isles, as well as to the Maghreb.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Most modern Europeans derive a significant part of their ancestry from these Neolithic Anatolian farmers.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Levantines also have significant Neolithic Anatolian farmer ancestry from post-Bronze Age migrations.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] About 6,500 years ago and thereafter, Anatolians became more genetically homogeneous due to eastern inflow.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Earlier forms of Anatolian and non–Indo-European languages such as Hattic and Hurrian were likely spoken by migrants and locals participating in this great mixture.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Steppe ancestry is also absent in Anatolians until the Bronze Age.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Neolithic Anatolia has been proposed as the homeland of the Indo-European language family, although linguists tend to favour a later origin in the steppes north of the Black Sea.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] However, it is clear that the Anatolian languages, the earliest attested branch of Indo-European, have been spoken in Anatolia since at least the 19th century BCE.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolia's historical records start with clay tablets from approximately around 2000 BC that were found in modern-day Kültepe.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] These tablets belonged to an Assyrian trade colony.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The languages in Anatolia at that time included Hattian, Hurrian, Hittite, Luwian, and Palaic.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The earliest historically attested populations of Anatolia were the Hattians in central Anatolia, and Hurrians further to the east.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Hattians were an indigenous people, whose main centre was the city of Hattush.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Affiliation of Hattian language remains unclear, while Hurrian language belongs to a distinctive family of Hurro-Urartian languages.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] All of those languages are extinct; relationships with indigenous languages of the Caucasus have been proposed, but are not generally accepted.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The region became famous for exporting raw materials.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Organized trade between Anatolia and Mesopotamia started to emerge during the period of the Akkadian Empire, and was continued and intensified during the period of the Old Assyrian Empire, between the 21st and the 18th centuries BCE.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Assyrian traders were bringing tin and textiles in exchange for copper, silver or gold.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] 20th century BCE, found in Anatolia at the Assyrian colony of Kanesh, use an advanced system of trading computations and credit lines.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Hattian rulers were gradually replaced by Hittite rulers.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Hittite kingdom was a large kingdom in Central Anatolia, with its capital of Hattusa.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] It co-existed in Anatolia with Palaians and Luwians, approximately between 1700 and 1200 BC.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] As the Hittite kingdom was disintegrating, further waves of Indo-European peoples migrated from southeastern Europe, which was followed by warfare.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] It is not known if the Trojan War is based on historical events.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Troy's Late Bronze Age layers matches most with *Iliad*'s story.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Around 750 BC, Phrygia had been established, with its two centres in Gordium and modern-day Kayseri.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Phrygians spoke an Indo-European language, which was closer to Greek than Anatolian languages.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Phrygians shared Anatolia with Neo-Hittites and Urartu.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Luwian-speakers were probably the majority in various Anatolian Neo-Hittite states.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Urartians spoke a non-Indo-European language and their capital was around Lake Van.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Urartu and Phrygia fell in seventh century BC.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] They were replaced by Carians, Lycians and Lydians.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] These three cultures "can be considered a reassertion of the ancient, indigenous culture of the Hattian cities of Anatolia".
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] , which was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage Site List in 2017.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In the late Bronze Age, there were three or four Greek-speaking settlements in Anatolia, including Miletus.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Around 1200–1000 BC, Greeks started migrating to the west coast of Anatolia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The size of these migrations are unknown.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Important cities included Miletus, Ephesus, Halicarnassus, Smyrna (now İzmir) and others These settlements were grouped as Aeolis, Ionia, and Doris, after the specific Greek groups that settled them.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] By 900 BC, Greek settlements emerged across the west coast of Anatolia from Knidos in the south all the way to the entrance of the Hellespont in the north.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In the Anatolian interior, Greek culture had limited influence until the time of Alexander the Great; Greek settlements "largely (although not exclusively)" existed on the western coast of Anatolia in the early Iron Age.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Further Greek colonization in Anatolia was led by Miletus and Megara in 750–480 BC, particularly in the Sea of Marmara and the Black Sea; settlements were also established in the south coast of Anatolia, at Phaselis, Aspendos, and Side.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Some archaeological evidence supports ancient Greeks' migration myths about the Ionian Migration not being a "virgin soil foundation", with a pre-Greek population present.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Aeolian and Ionian Greeks, refugees from their former Mycenaean kingdoms, mixed through marriages with native Anatolians.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In the late eighth century BC, the Greek cities of Anatolia maintained familial, linguistic, and religious connections to their close relatives on the Greek mainland.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Around 750 BC, Greeks in Anatolia started to differentiate themselves from other Anatolians, whom they regarded as barbarians, through the concept of the polis.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Greek city-states emerged in Anatolian western coasts as significant cultural and commercial hubs.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Their prosperity was based on extensive trade with the Anatolian peoples (Lycian, Lydian, Carian) and with other cities around the Aegean Sea.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] They also made numerous achievements in philosophy, science, architecture, and literature.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In Classical antiquity, Anatolia was described by the Ancient Greek historian Herodotus and later historians as divided into regions that were diverse in culture, language, and religious practices.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The northern regions included Bithynia, Paphlagonia, and Pontus; to the west were Mysia, Lydia, and Caria; and Lycia, Pamphylia, and Cilicia belonged to the southern shore.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] There were also several inland regions: Phrygia, Cappadocia, Pisidia, and Galatia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolia is known as the birthplace of minted coinage (as opposed to unminted coinage, which first appears in Mesopotamia at a much earlier date) as a medium of exchange, sometime in the 7th century BCE in Lydia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The use of minted coins continued to flourish during the Greek and Roman eras.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] During the 6th century BCE, all of Anatolia was conquered by the Persian Achaemenid Empire, the Persians having usurped the Medes as the dominant dynasty of Persia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In 499 BCE, the Ionian city-states on the west coast of Anatolia rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Ionian Revolt, as it became known, though quelled, initiated the Greco-Persian Wars, which ended in a Greek victory in 449 BCE, and the Ionian cities regained their independence.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] By the Peace of Antalcidas (387 BCE), which ended the Corinthian War, Persia regained control over Ionia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In 334 BCE, the Macedonian Greek king Alexander the Great conquered the Anatolian peninsula from the Achaemenid Persian Empire.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Alexander restored democracy in the Greek cities of Anatolia and was greeted by them as a liberator.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Lydians and Carians also hailed Alexander.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Alexander's conquest opened up the interior of Asia Minor to Greek settlement and influence.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolian cities transformed themselves into Hellenic-style poleis, and cities in Caria, Lydia, Lycia and Cilicia adopted Greek language, culture and institutions.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Following the death of Alexander the Great and the subsequent breakup of the Macedonian Empire, Anatolia was ruled by a series of Hellenistic kingdoms, such as the Attalids of Pergamum and the Seleucids, the latter controlling most of Anatolia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] A period of peaceful Hellenization followed, such that the local Anatolian languages had been supplanted by Greek by the 1st century BCE.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In 133 BCE, the last Attalid king bequeathed his kingdom to the Roman Republic; western and central Anatolia came under Roman control, but Hellenistic culture remained predominant.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Mithridates VI Eupator, ruler of the Kingdom of Pontus in northern Anatolia, waged war against the Roman Republic in the year 88 BCE in order to halt the advance of Roman hegemony in the Aegean Sea region.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Mithridates VI sought to dominate Asia Minor and the Black Sea region, waging several hard-fought but ultimately unsuccessful wars (the Mithridatic Wars) to break Roman dominion over Asia and the Hellenic world.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] He has been called the greatest ruler of the Kingdom of Pontus.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] His ally and son-in-law, Tigranes the Great of Armenia (r.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] 95 – 55 BCE), briefly conquered significant portions of Anatolia, including Cilicia, Cappadocia, Sophene and perhaps Galatia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] After the first division of the Roman Empire, Anatolia became part of the Eastern Roman Empire, otherwise known as the Byzantine Empire or Byzantium.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In the 1st century CE, Anatolia became one of the first places where Christianity spread, so that by the 4th century CE, western and central Anatolia were overwhelmingly Christian and Greek-speaking.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Byzantine Anatolia was one of the wealthiest and most densely populated places in the Later Roman Empire.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolia's wealth grew during the 4th and 5th centuries thanks, in part, to the Pilgrim's Road that ran through the peninsula.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Literary evidence about the rural landscape stems from the Christian hagiographies of the 6th-century Nicholas of Sion and 7th-century Theodore of Sykeon.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Large and prosperous urban centres of Byzantine Anatolia included Assos, Ephesus, Miletus, Nicaea, Pergamum, Priene, Sardis, and Aphrodisias.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] From the mid-5th century onwards, urbanism was affected negatively and began to decline, while the rural areas reached unprecedented levels of prosperity in the region.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Historians and scholars continue to debate the cause of the urban decline in Byzantine Anatolia between the 6th and 7th centuries, variously attributing it to the Plague of Justinian (541), the Byzantine–Sasanian War (602–628), and the Arab invasion of the Levant (634–638).
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In the 10 years following the Battle of Manzikert in 1071, the Seljuk Turks from Central Asia migrated over large areas of Anatolia, with particular concentrations around the northwestern rim.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In the following century, the Byzantines managed to reassert their control in western and northern Anatolia.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Control of Anatolia was then split between the Byzantine Empire and the Seljuk Sultanate of Rûm, with the Byzantine holdings gradually being reduced.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Fourth Crusade would prove to be a grave challenge to the Byzantine Empire.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The loss of a central authority figure shattered the empire, breaking it into four major successor states that each held sway over different parts of the empire.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Two of these states, the Empire of Nicaea and the Empire of Trebizond, would contend for the remains of the empire in Anatolia, with the Nicaean Empire holding the northwestern coast and the Trapezuntine empire holding the northeastern coast.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] In 1255, the Mongols swept through eastern and central Anatolia, and would remain until 1335.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Ilkhanate garrison was stationed near Ankara.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] After the decline of the Ilkhanate from 1335 to 1353, the Mongol Empire's legacy in the region was the Uyghur Eretna Dynasty that was overthrown by Kadi Burhan al-Din in 1381.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] By the end of the 14th century, most of Anatolia was controlled by various Anatolian beyliks.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Smyrna fell in 1330, and the last Byzantine stronghold in Anatolia, Philadelphia, fell in 1390.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Turkmen Beyliks were under the control of the Mongols, at least nominally, through declining Seljuk Sultans.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Beyliks did not mint coins in the names of their own leaders while they remained under the suzerainty of the Mongol Ilkhanids.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Ottoman ruler Osman I was the first Turkish ruler who minted coins in his own name in 1320s; they bear the legend "Minted by Osman son of Ertugrul".
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Since the minting of coins was a prerogative accorded in Islamic practice only to a sovereign, it can be considered that the Ottoman Turks had become formally independent from the Mongol Khans.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Among the Turkish leaders, the Ottomans emerged as great power under Osman I and his son Orhan.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Anatolian beyliks were successively absorbed into the rising Ottoman Empire during the 15th century.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] It is not well understood how the Osmanlı ('Ottoman Turks'), came to dominate their neighbours, as the history of medieval Anatolia is still little known.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Ottomans completed the conquest of the peninsula in 1517 with the taking of Halicarnassus (modern Bodrum) from the Knights of Saint John.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] A continuous reverse migration occurred since the early 19th century, when Greeks from Anatolia, Constantinople and Pontus area migrated toward the newly independent Kingdom of Greece, and also towards the United States, the southern part of the Russian Empire, Latin America, and the rest of Europe.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolia remained multi-ethnic until the early 20th century (see the rise of nationalism under the Ottoman Empire).
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] During World War I, the Armenian genocide, the Greek genocide (especially in Pontus), and the Assyrian genocide almost entirely removed the ancient indigenous communities of Armenian, Greek, and Assyrian populations in Anatolia and surrounding regions.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Following the Greco-Turkish War of 1919–1922, most remaining ethnic Anatolian Greeks were forced out during the 1923 population exchange between Greece and Turkey.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Of the remainder, most have left Turkey since then, leaving fewer than 5,000 Greeks in Anatolia today.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] According to Morris and Ze'evi, 4 million Christians were ethnically cleansed from Asia minor by the Turks from 1894 to 1924.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolia's terrain is structurally complex.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] A central massif composed of uplifted blocks and downfolded troughs, covered by recent deposits and giving the appearance of a plateau with rough terrain, is wedged between two folded mountain ranges that converge in the east.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] True lowland is confined to a few narrow coastal strips along the Aegean, Mediterranean, and the Black Sea coasts.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] There are two mountain ranges in southern Anatolia: the Taurus and the Zagros Mountains.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Anatolia has a varied range of climates.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The central plateau is characterized by a continental climate, with hot summers and cold, snowy winters.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The south and west coasts enjoy a typical Mediterranean climate, with mild rainy winters and warm, dry summers.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The Black Sea and Marmara coasts have a temperate oceanic climate, with warm, foggy summers and much rainfall throughout the year.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] There is a diverse number of plant and animal communities.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The mountains and coastal plain of northern Anatolia experience a humid and mild climate.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] There are temperate broadleaf, mixed and coniferous forests.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] The central and eastern plateau, with its drier continental climate, has deciduous forests and forest steppes.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] Western and southern Anatolia, which have a Mediterranean climate, contain Mediterranean forests, woodlands, and scrub ecoregions.
[src:ausonius/asia-minor] All have populations of more than 500,000.
[src:ausonius/ausones] "**Ausones**" (Ancient Greek: Αὔσονες; Italian: *Ausoni*), the original name and the extant Greek form for the Latin "Aurunci", was a name applied by Greek writers to describe various Italic peoples inhabiting the southern and central regions of Italy.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The term was used, specifically, to denote the particular tribe which Livy termed the Aurunci, but later it was applied to all Italians, and Ausonia became a poetic term, in Greek and Latin, for Italy itself.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The usage, by ancient writers, in regard to national appellations is very vague and fluctuating, perhaps in no instance more so than in the case of the Ausones or Ausonians.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Originally, "Aurunci" was the appellation given by the Romans to the people called "Ausones" by the Greeks: Indeed, the two names are merely different forms of the same, as around the 4th century BC, Latin medial "s" (at this point representing [z]) shifted to “r” (pronounced [r]).
[src:ausonius/ausones] The identity of the two is distinctly asserted by Servius, and clearly implied by Cassius Dio, where he says that the name of Ausonia was properly applied only to the land of the Auruncans, between the Volscians and the Campanians.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Nevertheless, it does not appear that the name "Aurunci" was ever employed by the Romans in the vague and extensive sense in which that of "Ausones" was used by the Greeks.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Further, it seems, by the later period of the fourth century BC, that the Romans came to distinguish the two names as applying to two separate political tribes of the same race.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Evidently two parts of one people, both dwelling on the frontiers of Latium and Campania.
[src:ausonius/ausones] It is possible the Ausonians may have also been identical with the Oscans (Opicans), as they were occasionally referred to by the same name.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Aristotle expressly states that the part of Italy towards Tyrrhenia was inhabited by the Opicans, "who were called, both formerly and in his time, by the additional name of Ausones".
[src:ausonius/ausones] Antiochus of Syracuse stated, that Campania was at first occupied by the Opicans, "who were also called Ausonians".
[src:ausonius/ausones] Hecataeus also seems to have had the same opinion as Antiochus, as he termed Nola in Campania "a city of the Ausones ".
[src:ausonius/ausones] Polybius, on the contrary, regarded the two nations as different and spoke of Campania as inhabited by the Ausonians and Opicans.
[src:ausonius/ausones] This does not necessarily prove that they were really distinct, as some authors mention the Opicans and Oscans as if they were two different nations when they are clearly the same.
[src:ausonius/ausones] However, the use of "Ausones" as identical with that of the Opicans may simply be due to the fact that "Ausones" was used as a vague term for all inhabitants of the Italian peninsula, as stated above.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The precise relation in which they were considered as having to the Opicans or Oscans it is impossible to determine, nor perhaps were the ideas of the Greeks themselves about this very clear and definite.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The passages already cited prove that they were considered as occupying the western coast of Campania, on which account the Lower Sea (*Mare Inferum*, as it was termed by the Romans), known subsequently as the Tyrrhenian Sea, was in early ages commonly termed by the Greeks the Ausonian Sea.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Other accounts, however, represent them as originally an inland people, dwelling in the mountains about Beneventum.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Scymnus of Chios also writes of them as occupying an inland region; and Strabo states that they had occupied the mountain tract above the Pontine marshes, and in Roman history only with Volscians.
[src:ausonius/ausones] But they seem to have been regarded by the best authorities as distinct from the Oenotrians, or Pelasgic nations, which inhabited the southern parts of the peninsula; though other authors certainly confounded them.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Hellanicus of Lesbos, according to Dionysius of Halicarnassus wrote of the Ausonians as crossing over into Sicily under their king Siculus, where the people meant are clearly the Siculi.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Again, Strabo wrote of Temesa as founded by the Ausones, where he must probably mean the Oenotrians, the only people whom we know of as inhabiting these regions before the arrival of the Greeks.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The use of the name of Ausonia for the whole Italian peninsula was merely poetical, at least it is not found in any extant prose writer; and Dionysius indicates that it was used by the Greeks in very early times, associates it with Hesperia and Saturnia, both of them obviously poetical appellations.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Apollonius Rhodius, a little later, seems to use the name of Ausonia precisely in the sense in which it is employed by Dionysius Periegetes and other Greek poets of later times (for the whole Italian peninsula).
[src:ausonius/ausones] It was probably only adopted by the Alexandrian writers as a poetical equivalent for Italia, a name which is not found in any poets of that period.
[src:ausonius/ausones] From them, the name of Ausonia was adopted by the Roman poets in the same sense, and at a later period became not uncommon even in prose writers.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The etymology of the name of Ausones is uncertain, but it seems not improbable that it is originally connected with the same root as Oscus or Opicus.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The first Greek settlers found Italy inhabited by three major populations: Ausones, Oenotrians and Iapyges.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The Ausones spoke an Indo-European language.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The core of the Ausonian people lived in a territory termed Ausonia: during the 8th century BC it included what is now southern Lazio and Campania until the Sele river.
[src:ausonius/ausones] In one passage Livy speaks of Cales as their chief city; but a little later, he tells us that they had three cities, Ausona, Minturnae, and Vescia, all of which seem to have been situated in the plains bordering on the Liris, not far from its outlet.
[src:ausonius/ausones] At this period, they were certainly an inconsiderable tribe and were able to offer but little resistance to the Romans.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Their city of Cales was captured, and soon after occupied by a Roman colony, 333 BC; and though a few years afterwards the success of the Samnites at Lautulae induced them to rebel, their three remaining towns were easily reduced by the Roman consuls, and their inhabitants put to the sword.
[src:ausonius/ausones] On this occasion, Livy tells us that "the Ausonian nation was destroyed"; It is certain that its name does not again appear in history, and is only noticed by Pliny among the extinct races which had formerly inhabited Latium.
[src:ausonius/ausones] According to different classical sources the Ausones were also settled in Calabria.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The Ausones allied with the Samnites against the Romans.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The main Ausonian cities of Ausona, Minturnae, Vescia and Sinuessa, according to Livy were destroyed.
[src:ausonius/ausones] According to a legend told by Diodorus Siculus, the king of the Ausones was Auson, son of Ulysses and Circe (or Calypso).
[src:ausonius/ausones] The son of Auson was Liparus, from whence the Lipari Islands derive their name.
[src:ausonius/ausones] From 1240 to 850 BC, the Aeolian Islands were occupied by a group of Ausones brought there by the legendary Liparus.
[src:ausonius/ausones] According to a legend Liparus is succeeded by Aeolus whose house, according to Homer, gave hospitality to Ulysses.
[src:ausonius/ausones] This continuous occupation may have been interrupted violently when, during the late 9th century BC, the Ausonian civilisation site, Lipara, on the island of Lipari was burned and apparently not rebuilt.
[src:ausonius/ausones] Around 1270 BC part of the Ausones relocated from Campania to Sicily.
[src:ausonius/ausones] The excavations on Lipari have revealed an assemblage which shares many features with those of contemporary Southern Italy (in its Subapennine-Protovillanovan phases).
[src:ausonius/ausones] This insular culture has been named as Ausonian I (1250/1200–1150 BC) and II (1150–850 BC) and associated with the Pantalica I and II (Cassibile) phases in Sicily (See Luigi Bernabò Brea).
[src:ausonius/ausones] Cales, in the commune of Calvi Risorta (province of Caserta, Campania), of which remains have been found, has been identified as an Ausonian city.
[src:ausonius/ausones] In the park of Roccamonfina, remains of a line of polygonal masonry walls belonging to the Ausonian civilization have been discovered.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] 310 in Burdigala (now Bordeaux), the son of Julius Ausonius (c.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] 290 – 378), a physician of Greek ancestry, and Aemilia Aeonia, daughter of Caecilius Argicius Arborius, descended on both sides from established, land-owning Gallo-Roman families of southwestern Gaul.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Ausonius was given a strict upbringing by his aunt and grandmother, both named Aemilia.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] He received an excellent education at Bordeaux and at Toulouse, where his maternal uncle, Aemilius Magnus Arborius, was a professor.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Ausonius did well in grammar and rhetoric, but professed that his progress in Greek was unsatisfactory.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] In 328 Arborius was summoned to Constantinople to become tutor to Constans, the youngest son of Constantine the Great, whereupon Ausonius returned to Bordeaux to complete his education under the rhetorician Minervius Alcimus.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] He had a sister, Dryadia, who lived to 60, a sister Aemilia Melania, who died in infancy, as well as a younger brother Avitianus, who died before reaching puberty, whom Ausonius laments in his *Parentalia*.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Having completed his studies, he trained for some time as an advocate, but he preferred teaching.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] In 334 he became a *grammaticus* (instructor) at a school of rhetoric in Bordeaux and afterwards a *rhetor* or professor.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] His teaching attracted many pupils, some of whom became eminent in public life.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] His most famous pupil was the poet Paulinus, who later became a Christian and Bishop of Nola.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] After thirty years of that work, Ausonius was summoned by Emperor Valentinian I to teach his son, Gratian, the heir-apparent.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] When Valentinian took Gratian on the German campaigns of 368–369, Ausonius accompanied them.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Ausonius turned literary skill into political capital.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] In recognition of his services emperor Valentinian bestowed on Ausonius the rank of quaestor.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] His presence at court gave Ausonius the opportunity to connect with a number of influential people.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] In 369, he met Quintus Aurelius Symmachus; their friendship proved mutually beneficial.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Gratian liked and respected his tutor, and when he became emperor in 375, he began bestowing on Ausonius and his family the highest civil honors.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] That year Ausonius was made Praetorian Prefect of Gaul, campaigned against the Alemanni and received as part of his booty a slave girl, Bissula (to whom he addressed a poem), and his father, though nearly ninety years old, was given the rank of prefect of Illyricum.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] In 376 Ausonius's son, Hesperius, was made proconsul of Africa.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] In 379 Ausonius was awarded the consulate, the highest Roman honour.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] In 383, the army of Britain, led by Magnus Maximus, revolted against Gratian and assassinated him at Lyons; and when Emperor Valentinian II was driven out of Italy, Ausonius retired to his estates near Burdigala (now Bordeaux), in Gaul.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Magnus Maximus was overthrown by Emperor Theodosius I in 388, but Ausonius did not leave his country estates.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] They were, he says, his *nidus senectutis*, the "nest of his old age", and there, he spent the rest of his days, composing poetry and writing to many eminent contemporaries, several of whom had been his pupils.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] His estates supposedly included the land now owned by Château Ausone, which takes its name from him.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Ausonius appears to have been a late convert to Christianity.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] His grandson, Paulinus of Pella, was also a poet.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] His works attest to the devastation that Ausonius's Gaul would face soon after his death.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Although admired by his contemporaries, the writings of Ausonius have not since been ranked among Latin literature's finest.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] His style is easy and fluent, and his *Mosella* is appreciated for its evocation of the life and the country along the River Moselle, but he is considered derivative and unoriginal.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Edward Gibbon pronounced in his *Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* that "the poetical fame of Ausonius condemns the taste of his age".
[src:ausonius/ausonius] The excerpt sheds new light on the development of Roman technology in using water power for different applications.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] It is one of the rare references in Roman literature to water mills used to cut stone, but that is a logical consequence of the application of water power to mechanical sawing of stone and presumably wood also.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Earlier references to the widespread use of mills occur in Vitruvius in his *De Architectura* of c.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] 25 BC, and the *Naturalis Historia* of Pliny the Elder published in 77 AD.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] Such applications of mills would multiply after the fall of the empire through the Middle Ages into the modern era.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] The mills at Barbegal, in southern France, are famous for their application of water power to grinding grain to make flour and were built in the 1st century AD.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] They consisted of 16 mills in a parallel sequence on a hill near Arles.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] The construction of a saw mill is even simpler than a flour or grinding mill since no gearing is needed, and the rotary saw blade can be driven directly from the water wheel axle, as the example of Sutter's Mill, California, shows.
[src:ausonius/ausonius] However, a different mechanism is shown by the sawmill at Hieropolis, Asia Minor, involving a frame saw that is operated by a crank and connecting rod.
